Animated GIF creation

The following Gif Was created to visualise/animate the North shore swimming club.

#importing images for GIF

dive_1 <- image_read("https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2020/04/23/12/15/jump-5082231_1280.png") %>%
          image_scale(400) %>%
          image_convert(colorspace = "sRGB")

dive_2 <- image_read("https://i.pinimg.com/564x/d3/8b/98/d38b984f5d49b84182827df775a66101.jpg") %>%
          image_scale(400)

splash <- image_read("https://www.pngitem.com/pimgs/m/50-506407_transparent-water-splashes-clipart-cartoon-water-splash-png.png") %>%
          image_scale(400)

logo <- image_read("https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQU_rtgrOahZjQClgwcqCeSaCYxQTNO2wBTwz5dumu1ohLrmqi3OcBIpWvtD5BSv6w4Ri8&usqp=CAU") %>%
        image_scale(400)


#Creating a text frame

NSS_text <- image_blank(width = 400, height = 400, color = "#FFF700") %>%
            image_annotate(text = "#1\nSwim Club\nin NZ", color = "#0042FF", size = 80, gravity = "center", font = "Impact") %>%
            image_morph(2)


#Morphing two frames together for added effect

splash_logo <- c(splash, logo) %>%
                image_morph(frames = 1.5)


#Putting the GIF together

frames <- c(dive_1, dive_2, splash_logo, NSS_text) %>%
            image_morph(frames = 2)

NSS_GIF <- image_animate(frames, fps = 2.5)


NSS_GIF

Learning reflection

The main important idea I took away from module 1: creating HTML by combining modern technologies; was how HTMLs can be used to create webpages with r code embedded within the html to create graphics. This module also showed me how I can incorporate CSS code to make my htmls look good.

I am very curious about exploring further into data bases and how we can optimise the way in which we import and analyse data. I do a lot of performance analysis work within a sporting environment so through data technologies I would like to find a way to increase my efficiency when working with data to start to automate my analysis and reporting on the data.
